06206nam a22008895i 9783110610994DE-B159720210526051534.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210526t20202020gw     fo  d z      eng d  a2020933278  a97831106109947 a10.1515/97831106109942doi  a(DE-B1597)527002  a(OCoLC)1163879223  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 4aPA3978b.E5 2020 7aLIT0041902bisacsh04a882/.012231 aBaechle, Nicholas, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aAesthetic Response and Traditional Social Valuation in Euripides’ ›Electra‹ :bTragic ›Kunstsprache‹ and the ›kharaktēr‹ of Heroes /cNicholas Baechle. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (IX, 162 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aBeiträge zur Altertumskunde ;v37900tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgements -- tIntroduction: The complex analogy between social appearance and stylistic presentation and the provocations to cultural self-awareness played out in Euripides’ Electra -- tI The initial presentation of the Old Man: Characterization and stylistic presentation of an oddly mundane, even anti-heroic, tragic character -- tII The initial presentation of Orestes: Appearance, eugeneia, and social expectations about character and agency -- tIII Orestes, eugeneia, and aesthetic expectations about heroic characterization and agency -- tIV Achilles and the first stasimon: Stylistic effect and the “appearance” of an heroic character -- tV The Old Man again: The Kunstsprache and character construction -- tVI The Kunstsprache, defamiliarization, and the metapoetics of character construction -- tVII The Old Man and Orestes: The problem of eugeneia in the second episode -- tVIII Metapoetics in the abortive first section of the recognition scene -- tIX The recognition proper: the kharaktēr of tragic heroes -- tX Unquestioned assumptions and the aesthetics of valuation: What can be made of this Orestes? -- tConclusion: Cultural context and tradition: Continuity of substance and appearance and the basis of the complex analogy -- tWorks cited -- tSubject index0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aEuripides’ Electra opened up for its audience an opportunity to become self-aware as to the appeal of tragic Kunstsprache: it both reflected and sustained traditional, aristocratically-inflected assumptions about the continuity of appearance and substance, even in a radical democracy. A complex analogy between social and aesthetic valuation is played out and brought to light. The characterization of Orestes early in the play demonstrates how social appearances made clear the identity of well-born, and how they were still assumed to indicate superior virtue and agency. On the aesthetic side of the analogy, one of the functions of tragic diction, as an essential indication of heroic character and agency, comes into view in a dramatic and thematic sequence that begins with Achilles ode and ends with the planning of the murders. Serious doubts are created as to whether Orestes will realize the assumed potential inherent in his heroic genealogy and, at the same time, as to whether the components of his character as an aesthetic construct are congruent with such qualities and agency. Both sides of this complex analogy are thus problematized, and, at a metapoetic level, its nature and bases are exposed for reflection.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 4aElektra. 4aEuripides. 4aGriechische Literatur. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Ancient & Classical.2bisacsh  aElectra.  aEuripides.  aaesthetics.  a social history.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Ebook Package 2020z978311069627108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Ebook P